ECON 5343-001
CAUSAL INFERENCE FOR BUSINESS DECISIONS
Addresses how firms distill useful business intelligence from various sources of raw data. Introduces various methods to determine what results of strategic interventions were caused by, rather than merely correlated with them. The course examines threats to causal identification such as reverse causality, sample selection bias, and unobserved covariates. Topics may include: Randomized Experiments and Quasi-Experiments, Sample Selection Models, Propensity Score Matching, Instrumental Variables Methods, Differences-in-Differences, and Regression Discontinuity.


